ire, Wales"},"da":{"about 1323–":"omkring 1323–Afdød","1323–Male":"1323–Afdød","1323–Female":"1323–Afdød","1350–Male":"1350–Afdød","1308–1355":"1308–1355","1308–Female":"1308–Afdød","1323":"1323","1355":"1355","about 1323":"omkring 1323","1350":"1350","1308":"1308","Pembrokeshire, Wales":"Pembrokeshire, Wales","Woodstock, Pembrokeshire, Wales":"Woodstock, Pembrokeshire, Wales"},"nl":{"about 1323–":"circa 1323–Overleden","1323–Male":"1323–Overleden","1323–Female":"1323–Overleden","1350–Male":"1350–Overleden","1308–1355":"1308–1355","1308–Female":"1308–Overleden","1323":"1323","1355":"1355","about 1323":"circa 1323","1350":"1350","1308":"1308","Pembrokeshire, Wales":"Pembrokeshire, Wales","Woodstock, Pembrokeshire, Wales":"Woodstock, Pembrokeshire, Wales"},"en":{"about 1323–":"about 1323–Deceased","1323–Male":"1323–Deceased","1323–Female":"1323–Deceased","1350–Male":"1350–Deceased","1308–1355":"1308–1355","1308–Female":"1308–Deceased","1323":"1323","1355":"1355","about 1323":"about 1323","1350":"1350","1308":"1308","Pembrokeshire, Wales":"Pembrokeshire, Wales","Woodstock, Pembrokeshire, Wales":"Woodstock, Pembrokeshire, Wales","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Howell","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Welsh and English: in the Welsh border counties, from the Welsh male personal name <i>Hywel</i> ‘eminent’, popular since the Middle Ages particularly in honor of the great 10th-century law-giving Welsh king. The name may also arise from the Breton personal name <i>Houuel</i>, <i>Huwel</i>, <i>Huwal</i>, <i>Howael</i>, cognate with the Welsh name. Bretons were especially numerous in the eastern counties of England. See   Powell  .","English: perhaps from a Middle English personal name <i>Huwel</i> (spelled <i>Howel</i>), a shortening of <i>Huwelot</i> or <i>Huelin</i> (see   Hewlett   and   Huling  ), both pet forms of Middle English <i>Huw</i> (see   Hugh  ).","English: habitational name from Howell (Lincolnshire), from an uncertain initial element + Old English <i>wella</i> ‘well, spring, stream’."],"variants":[{"name":"Howle","meanings":["English and Welsh:","variant of   Howell  .","variant of   Hole  ."]},{"name":"Howells","meanings":["English and Welsh (Glamorgan): variant of   Howell  , with genitival or post-medieval excrescent English <i>-s</i>.","English: perhaps occasionally a nickname for someone who was fearless, from Middle English <i>houe</i>, <i>houwe</i> ‘anxiety, fear’ (Old English <i>hogu</i> or <i>hoga</i>) + <i>les</i> ‘less’. If this has survived as a modern surname, its pronunciation has been influenced by that of the name in 1 above.","English: variant of   Holes  ."]},{"name":"Powell","meanings":["Welsh: Anglicized form of Welsh <i>ap Hywel</i> ‘son of <i>Hywel</i>’, a personal name meaning ‘eminent’ (see   Howell  ).","Irish: mainly of Welsh origin as in 1 above, but sometimes a surname adopted as equivalent of Gaelic <b>Mac Giolla Phóil</b> ‘son of the servant of Saint Paul’ (see   Guilfoyle  ).","English: variant of   Paul   or   Poole  ."]}]},{"name":"ap","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Kurt, Eberhard.","German: variant of   Axt  .","Swedish: soldier's name, apparently from <i>ax</i> ‘ear (i.e. the part of a cereal plant which contains its flowers or seeds)’."],"variants":[{"name":"Akes","meanings":["German: possibly a variant of   Ax  . The surname <i>Akes</i> is virtually non-existing in Germany."]},{"name":"Axt","meanings":["German: metonymic occupational name for a woodcutter, carpenter, or maker of axes, from Middle High German <i>ackes</i>, <i>axt-</i> ‘axe’."]}]},{"name":"Hywell","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Americanized form of German   Heisel  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Heisel","meanings":["South German: from a pet form of   Heiss  ."]}]},{"name"